<div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden first:pt-[3px]"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><p>To use the <strong>pumping lemma</strong> to show that a language <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is not regular, you must follow these steps and select a specific <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;to make the proof work. Here's a structured approach:</p><h1>Pumping lemma can only be used to showing non regularity of a language,it doent mean that a language is regular if it satisfies.</h1><hr><h3>1. <strong>Understand the Pumping Lemma</strong></h3><p>The pumping lemma states that if <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is a regular language, then there exists a pumping length <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;such that for any&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; string <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w \in L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mi>w</mi><mi mathvnt="normal">∣</mi><mo>≥</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">|w| \geq p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;,</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;can be split into three parts <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">xyz</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>, satisfying:</p><ol><li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w = xyz</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>,</li><li><span class="katex"><span class="katexhml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">|xy| \leq p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;(the first <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;characters contain <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>),</li><li><span class="katex"><spss="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mi>y</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">|y| &gt; 0</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;(<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is not empty),</li><li>For all <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">i \geq 0</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><msup><mi>y</mi><mi>i</mi></msup><mi>z</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="applicati">xy^i z \in L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</li></ol><p>If you can find a string <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;that violates these conditions, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is not regular.</p><hr><h3>2. <strong>Pick a String <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span><br></span></strong></h3><p>The choice of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.02691em;">w</span></span></span></span> is crucial. Here's how you do it:</p><ul><li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.02691em;">w</span></span></span></span> should be long enough (<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mi>w</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mo>≥</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-te \geq p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>) so that the properties of the pumping lemma apply.</li><li>Select <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.02691em;">w</span></span></span></span> cleverly based on the structure of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;to make it impossible to pump <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;while keeping <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><msup><mi>y</mi><mi>i</mi></msup><mi>z</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">xy^i z \in L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</li></ul><hr><h3>3. <strong>Split <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w = xyz</annotation></semantics></math></span><br></span></strong></h3><ul><li>Since <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">|xy| \leq p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>, the substring <span class=<span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;lies entirely within the first <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;characters of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</li><li>Analyze all possible splits <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">xyz</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;to ensure at least one violates the pumping lemma.</li></ul><hr><h3>4. <strong>Pumping <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.625em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">y</span></span></span></span></strong></h3><ul><li>Consider pumping <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.625em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">y</span></span></span></span> (i.e., repeating it 0, 2, or more times) and check whether <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><msup><mi>y</mi><mi>i</mi></msup><mi>z</mi><mo mathvariant="normal">∉</mo><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">xy^i z \notin L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;for some <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo mathvariant="normal">≠</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">i \neq 1</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</li><li>If such <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">i</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;exists, the language <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="applion/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is not regular.</li></ul><hr><h3>Example Walkthrough</h3><p>Let’s show that the language <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>∣</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L = \{ a^n b^n \mid n \geq 0 \}</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is not regular.</p><ol><li><p><strong>Assume <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is regular.</strong> By the pumping lemma, there exists a pumping length <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><sem><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</p></li><li><p><strong>Choose <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</strong> Let <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>p</mi></msup><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>p</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w = a^p b^p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>. Clearly, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mi>w</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>p</mi><mo>≥</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">|w| = 2p \geq p</annotation></semantics></mspan></span>, so the lemma applies.</p></li><li><p><strong>Split <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w = xyz</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>:</strong></p><ul><li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>k</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x = a^k</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>m</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y = a^m</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>p</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">z = a^{p-k-m}b^p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>, where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">k + m \leq p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">m &gt; 0</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</li><li>This means <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;contains onan class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>'s.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Pump <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>:</strong> Try <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">i = 2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6595em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">i</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6444em;"></span><span class="mord">2</span></span></span></span> (pump <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.625em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">y</span></span></span></span> once):</p><ul><li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>p</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi>p</mi><</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>p</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">xy^2z = a^{k+m+m}a^{p-k-m}b^p = a^{p+m}b^p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</li><li>Now <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mi>a</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mo mathvariant="normal">≠</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi><mi>b</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">∣</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">|a| \neq |b|</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>, so <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>z</mi><mo mathvariant="normal">∉</mo><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">xy^2z \notin L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> The pumping lemma is violated, so "katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is not regular.</p></li></ol><hr><h3>Tips for Selecting <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.02691em;">w</span></span></span></span></h3><ul><li>Analyze the structure of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>: Look for patterns, such as dependencies between symbols or constraints on lengths.</li><li>Choose <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;such that it cannot satisfy the pumping lemma conditions under any split <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">xyz</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</li><li>If <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;contains constraints (e.g., equal numbers of different symbols), <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">w</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;should demonstrate these constraints.</li></ul></div></div>